Balance through engagement is still a major issue for Roberts, who can be slow and lumbering with his recovery footwork and inconsistent with his pad level management, and his stunt vision can improve as well. However, in spite of his limitations with recovery athleticism and flexibility, Roberts has the size, power, and physicality to hold up in a phone booth, and seal off corridors in gap schemes.

He projects as solid interior depth right away, and could take notable reps as a replacement-level starter.

name: Beau Stephens
analysis:
Beau Stephens was a central part of the Iowa Hawkeyes' Joe Moore Award-winning offensive line, and also boasts PFSN's highest individual OL Impact score of the 2025 season, with a grade of 94.1. At around 6'5", 315 pounds, Stephens has above-average size and mass, and is a solid athlete for his size, with very good burst off the line and even better range in space when he's able to open up his strides. Stephens is ultra-physical and tenacious in the run game, and technically sound in pass protection, with very good footwork efficiency, synergetic feel, and awareness.

Stephens' sub-32" arms can be a limitation at times; he's powerful in spite of that measurement, but he can be baited into over-reaching and lurching, and his latches aren't as strong against longer opponents. Additionally, in pass protection, Stephens still has room to improve his play strength and anchor footwork, and his balance at engagement is inconsistent. Nevertheless, Stephens passes the desired athletic and intangible thresholds, he's a gnarly competitor who relishes contact, and his flexibility is a surprising trump card that enables him to acquire leverage and engage his base consistently.

He projects as an instant depth piece and future starter.

name: Jack Strand
analysis:
Jack Strand is a notable sleeper in the 2026 NFL Draft, who's set to play in front of NFL scouts and evaluators at the American Bowl. At 6'5", 240 pounds, Strand quietly has many of the diagnostic qualities sought after in a NFL backup or developmental starter. He's a plus athlete at his size, with a live arm and elite arm elasticity, arm angle flexibility, and off-platform freedom.

On top of his strong physical foundation, Strand has shown he can ID coverages quickly and work through progressions, and though his trigger can be a bit faster still, he's capable of operating both in-structure and on the move at a high level. Strand still has room to clean up his mechanics and get more comfortable with faster-paced defenses, but he has very real upside worth banking on in the middle rounds.

name: Xavier Nwankpa
analysis:
Xavier Nwankpa came into Iowa City with a great deal of hype as a five-star recruit, and flashes in 2023 hinted at greater upside in 2024. Instead, Nwankpa's early-season struggles cascaded, and he lost reps on the defensive side of the ball down the stretch. He had his bright spots and flashed his tantalizing athletic upside, but there remains a need for greater consistency and further technical refinement as Nwankpa enters his fourth season.

A move from strong safety to free safety should help for the 6'2", 215-pound playmaker; he thrived as a middle-field ball-hawk in high school with 16 career HS picks. However, improvement with pedal and weave technique will be key in helping Nwankpa reach his ceiling.

name: Robert Henry Jr.
analysis:
Robert Henry Jr. was a small-school high school star who was forced to take the JUCO route early in his collegiate career. After distinguishing himself at Jones College in Mississippi, he was able to leverage his unheralded talent into a three-year opportunity with the UTSA Roadrunners.

Three years later, Henry is a legitimate NFL Draft prospect, after having amassed 408 carries for 2,339 yards and 27 touchdowns in his career. In 2025 alone, Henry rushed for a career-high 1,045 yards at almost seven yards per attempt. On film, it's not hard to see why Henry has been one of the most dynamic players in the Group of Six over the past few years.

At 5'9", 205 pounds, Henry is undersized, but as a mover, he's springy and explosive, with light feet, nimble lateral range, acute cutting flexibility, and the long-strider burst to take advantage of creases and cutback lanes. His natural creative athleticism as a runner is only maximized by his quick processing speed, cutback anticipation, pressing IQ, and adaptability. He'll turn 25 years old at the tail end of his rookie season, but Henry has the profile of an immediate contributor as a change-of-pace back, and he could produce even beyond that.

name: Jaydn Ott
analysis:
Jaydn Ott looked like a future early-round pick after a true sophomore season at California that saw him amass 1,315 yards and 12 touchdowns on 246 carries, earning first-team All-Pac-12 honors in the process. Ott's efficiency tanked in 2024, however, and a transfer to Oklahoma quickly proved fruitless; with the Sooners, Ott exited the summer buried on the depth chart, and barely saw the field in his final season. At his best, Ott proved he's an exciting talent.

He's quick and explosive, with a particular affinity for north-south running with his instinctive gap processing and vertical speed, and he's flashed high-level receiving versatility and RAC ability before. But NFL evaluators will have to vet his stark regression over the past two seasons, and even at his peak, he's lacking in terms of physicality, peripheral vision, and pass blocking utility. As it stands, Ott has immense buy-low potential on Day 3, with the natural talent to grow into a quality rotational sparkplug, but pressing questions to answer as well.

name: Nate Boerkircher
analysis:
Nate Boerkircher is a prime candidate to emerge as a "Jackson Hawes" style of late-round TE. He caught just 38 passes in a five-year career at Texas A&M, but distinguished himself in other ways for the Aggies. At around 6'4", 250 pounds, with solid functional length, Boerkircher is built well as a two-phase TE, and he makes his most effusive mark in the blocking phase.

He has a functional strength and power profile that can contend right away in the NFL, and he's a tenacious, technically-sound blocker as well. He acquires leverage well and consistently drives his feet through blocks, he understands attack angles, he engages with forceful hands and imposing push, and he's a competent pass protector who can serve as a sixth blocker on passing downs with his steady footwork and anchor. The same functional athleticism that makes Boerkircher so imposing as a moving blocker also underlies some moderate receiving upside; he's quick and explosive for his size, and flashes good hip mobility and stem IQ.

That said, his route tree is relatively under-developed, he's not the most flexible catch-point controller, and his hands can be inconsistent, particularly when gathering RAC passes. Boerkircher fits best as a TE2 or TE3 whose prime function is as an immediate run game catalyst.

name: Lewis Bond
analysis:
Lewis Bond developed from an unheralded three-star recruit in 2021 to an ultra-dependable primary option for the Boston College Eagles in 2025. In his final season, he accmulated 88 catches, 993 yards, and a touchdown, and he also put together a strong analytical profile. His PFSN WR Impact grade was a rock-solid 80.5, and per TruMedia, Bond also registered 2.29 yards per route run, a catch rate over expectation of 13.88%, and a miniscule 2.7% drop rate.

Despite being under 5'11" and 190 pounds, with sub-30" arms, Bond plays up to and beyond his size with his catch-point composure and hand strength, and he's an incredibly nuanced route runner and separator with high-level hip fluidity and flexibility underpinning his separation framework. At his size, Bond lacks ideal functional athleticism, as his speed and explosiveness measure closer to average than elite. That said, he's an exceedingly sound football player both before and at the catch, and he has the thickly-built midsection and lower body to supplement play strength in the RAC phase as well.

A likely mid-to-late-round target, Bond has immediate rotational appeal, and could be a future starting slot WR.

name: Rahsul Faison
analysis:
Rahsul Faison ran for almost 3,000 yards and 42 touchdowns as a high school senior, but academic issues derailed his early college career. He opted to take the JUCO path after greyshirting at Marshall -- first spending a year at Lackawanna College, before moving to Snow College in 2021. In 2022, Faison saw the field and produced at an efficient clip, and at last began cultivating FBS interest again.

At Utah State in 2023 and 2024, Faison totaled 1,845 yards and 14 TDs, before transferring to South Carolina for his final season. With the Gamecocks, Faison was mainly a rotational back, who was kept out of pass blocking duties more often than not, but his raw talent nonetheless flashed. At almost 220 pounds, Faison has unique explosive athleticism and elite hip flexibility and bend as a mover, and working in space, he shows glimpses of high-level peripheral vision and creative freedom, with a vast move arsenal at his size.

Faison will be a 26-year old rookie with an uncertain floor and ceiling, but as a late-round or PFA addition, he has the rare creative upside and receiving versatility to be a short-tenure gem in the right environment.

name: Diego Pavia
analysis:
Diego Pavia was one of the stars of the 2025 college football season. He began his collegiate career at New Mexico Military Institute after being overlooked as a high scool recruit, and leveraged a dominant second season at NMMI into an opportunity with the New Mexico State Aggies. With the Aggies, Pavia distinguished himself as a dynamic two-phase playmaker, and eventually ascended to the SEC as Vanderbilt's field general.

In 2025, Pavia was a Heisman finalist, and earned the top PFSN QB Impact score in the nation, with a grade of 94.8. Pavia's analytics inspire hope; he's an efficient, fairly accurate passer who avoids ill-advised risks, and he boasts a juiced-up and gritty running style. However, his on-field evaluation does leave questions.

His processing isn't quite NFL-caliber, nor is his arm strength, and even his athleticism might not be as prevalent against NFL talent. Pavia has the desired mobility, toughness, and quick-game utility to function as an NFL backup, but his ceiling is likely capped beyond that.

name: Behren Morton
analysis:
Behren Morton started at least four games in four of his five collegiate seasons, and was a full-time starter when available in his final three years. Though his career ended with a two-interception dud against the Oregon Ducks in the CFB Playoff Quarterfinal, Morton at least produced enough quality tape to make his way onto the NFL radar. At under 6'2" and just over 200 pounds, Morton isn't quite a protoypical passer, nor does he have the desired athleticism or high-end arm strength.

His durability has also been a recurring issue over the past few years. Those factors alone, when combined with his inconsistent post-snap processing and accuracy, likely set his ceiling as an NFL backup and spot-starter. That said, Morton at least has the arm elasticity to launch from different arm angles and layer pace and touch on throws, and he has some platform versatility in spite of his middling athleticism.

If he can keep refining his mental game and accuracy, he can carve out a respectable career.

name: Luke Altmyer
analysis:
Luke Altmyer was a four-star recruit out of high school, who ended up starting three seasons for the Illinois Fighting Illini. He closed out his collegiate career with his best season, completing 67% of his passes while throwing for over 3,000 yards, 22 touchdowns, and just five interceptions, while earning a strong PFSN QB Impact score of 85.6. As a prospect, Altmyer visibly lacks any elite traits.

His size is close to average, and his arm is only above-average at best. He's not a dynamic creator, nor is he a consistently elite anticipator. That said, he does have very good pre-snap and post-snap vision, he's reasonably accurate, he has good pocket depth discipline and navigation skills, and he's shown he can get the ball out decisively while not placing passes in harm's way.

Altmyer likely won't emerge as a long-term starter in the NFL, but he has the well-rounded -- if unspectacular -- profile to be a quality backup candidate on Day 3.

name: Sawyer Robertson
analysis:
Sawyer Robertson was one of the more productive quarterbacks on the college football stage over the past two seasons. Starting four games in 2023, Robertson's game was much less consistent over that early-career stretch, but he returned as a passer reimagined in 2024, throwing for over 3,000 yards and almost 30 scores while leading his team to a 7-4 record. In 2025, Robertson achieved career-highs in yardage (3,681) and passing TDs (31), and earned a spot on the Panini Senior Bowl roster.

As a likely Day 3 selection, Robertson has plenty of appealing qualities. Though his arm is above-average at best, he's a prototypical passer with very good creation capacity and underlying touchness, and with an extra year of starting experience, his pre-snap and post-snap vision, as well as his mechanical control, markedly improved in 2025. He can still experience shoulder misalignment and situational imprecision at times, and will attempt to force throws his arm doesn't quite have the juice for, but he has the baseline physical talent, mental acuity, and toughness of an ideal backup QB and safety blanket.

name: Cole Payton
analysis:
Cole Payton redshirted his first year at NDSU, and from 2022 through 2024, he was the backup to Cam Miller. He was utilized most often as a designed runner, but finally got his shot as a full-time starter in 2025. In his last season of eligibility, Payton passed for 2,719 yards, 16 touchdowns, and four interceptions on over 70% completion, while also running for 717 yards and 13 additional TDs.

Additionally, he ended the year with the second-highest PFSN QB Impact score in the FCS (89.7). The crux of Payton's appeal as a prospect is his physical talent. At 6'3", 233 pounds, he's a well-built prototype with elite explosive athleticism, bristling long speed, and a rocket arm that can generate high-end velocity from multiple launch points and angles.

But as a one-year starter, he's sorely lacking in-game reps, and his processing runs on the slow side as a result. Payton shouldn't be thrown into the fire right away as a field general, and is a developmental QB first, who could be utilized in certain Taysom Hill-esque packages early on. If he enters the right situation and has time to acclimate before getting needed reps, starting upside is present.

name: Jalen Farmer
analysis:
Jalen Farmer declared for the 2026 NFL Draft as a redshirt junior, after starting two full seasons for the Kentucky Wildcats and earning a strong 87.4 PFSN OL Impact score in his final season. As one might expect from a slightly younger prospect, Farmer is a bit underdeveloped in some technical areas, most notably his hand usage. His inconsistent hand replacement can allow pass-rushers to decouple and generate pressure later in reps, and at times, he's over-reliant on his explosion and mass as an obstructor in the run game.

Nevertheless, Farmer is a young and ascending prospect with an enticing physical foundation. At 6'5", 317 pounds, he has excellent lean mass, a thick and strong lower body, and good proportional length. With his initial explosion, mass, length, and mean mauler mentality, he can slab interior defenders off the line, as well as torque through and seal off gaps with his core strength.

And in pass protection, he has a naturally strong anchor and above-average leverage acquisition skills. His game needs more refinement before he can reach his ceiling, but that ceiling is a quality starter.

name: Patrick Payton
analysis:
Patrick Payton arrives at LSU as a fifth-year senior and one of college football's most experienced edge defenders, bringing 31.5 career tackles for loss and 16 sacks after starting 26 games at Florida State. Towering at 6'6", 255 pounds, Payton stands out for his long, twitchy frame and the ability to anchor the edge with length and power, shutting down run lanes and using his burst to disrupt upfield. While still raw as a pass rusher, he’s easily projectable thanks to his physical tools, outstanding pursuit range, and flexibility to flatten around the arc.

If he can continue developing his hand usage and add strength, Payton has the upside to become an early-round NFL Draft pick.

name: DJ Rogers
analysis:
DJ Rogers profiles as one of the more well-rounded two-phase TE prospects in the 2026 NFL Draft. He joined the Horned Frogs in 2021 and redshirted that year, and only caught seven passes through his first three seasons. The 2024 campaign saw Rogers become more involved as a primary TE, but he saved his best for last in 2025, catching 34 passes for 319 yards and two touchdowns, while putting up a PFSN TE Impact score of 78.6.

Rogers grades out as solid but unspectacular in most areas. He doesn't have elite explosion, speed, or quickness, but at least passes the requisite threshold in all athletic categories. As a route runner, he has a solid route tree and very good functional stem IQ, with the range to threaten vertically up seams and accrue RAC with creases of space.

And as a blocker, while he can still improve his play strength a bit, he has a good power profile, excels at squaring up his assignments and acquiring leverage, and is competent as an extra pass protector when called upon. With his non-elite athleticism, size, and at-times inconsistent hands, Rogers might never be a starting TE, but he can be a very good TE2 with multi-phase utility.

name: Fernando Carmona
analysis:
Fernando Carmona Jr. transferred to Arkansas from San Jose State in 2024, after starting two full seasons at left tackle and earning honorable mention All-Mountain West recognition in 2023. Upon arriving at Arkansas, he began his tenure with the Razorbacks at LT, but a streaky acclimation to SEC play led him to kick inside to left guard for his final season.

At guard, Carmona looked more comfortable -- registering an elite PFSN OL Impact grade of 91 -- and that's likely where he'll stick at the NFL level. Carmona's linear athleticism pops, and he has hyper-elite raw power capacity when he's able to work on the attack as a puller and climber. He's not shy about finishing opponents in the dirt, either -- though he can employ better discipline at times (10 penalties in 2025).

He's not overly flexible; he especially lacks in knee bend, and he needs to improve his leverage acquisition and pad level in pass protection. Still, Carmona brings experience, explosive straight-line athleticism, menacing power capacity, and relentless physicality. With improvements in leverage play and hand replacement, he can be an effective starter inside, with a particular affinity for gap schemes.

name: Will Kacmarek
analysis:
Will Kacmarek spent his first three seasons at Ohio, before transferring to play for the regional blue-blood: The Ohio State Buckeyes. At Ohio State, he served as a quality TE2 for two seasons, peaking in 2025 with 15 catches for 168 yards and a respectable PFSN TE Impact score of 76.7. Kacmarek never emerged as a starting talent at Ohio State, and lost reps to Max Klare in the passing game.

That said, Kacmarek maintained his value as a high-quality blocking presence. At 6'5", 259 pounds, with plus length and play strength, Kacmarek sizes up well in contact situations, and while his leverage, pad level maintenance, and leg drive post-contact can be more consistent, he engages with force, is capable of operating as a sixth pass-protector, and can be difficult for defenders to unlatch. As a receiver, Kacmarek's upside is visibly capped.

Athletically, he's not overly explosive, fluid, or balanced, with visible hip stiffness that constricts his route tree, and he's not very flexible in contortion situations. That said, Kacmarek's arm reach and strong hands provide measured value in red-zone and conversion scenarios. Best as a late-round pick or PFA, Kacmarek projects as a rotational TE and primary blocking TE in heavy personnel sets, whose toughness and role versatility set a stable floor.

name: Riley Mahlman
analysis:
Riley Mahlman has started 31 games to this point at Wisconsin, all at right tackle, and he's trending toward an NFL ascent. Standing at 6'7", 308 pounds, with arms that might measure shorter than 33", Mahlman has an unorthodox build, without ideal natural leverage or reach. And yet, he's a surprisingly well-rounded, if unspectacular, OT prospect.

For his size, he has impressive knee bend and flexibility, and can play with controlled lean to acquire leverage at contact. He's a nimble mover with stellar lateral recovery and balance, he brings visible knockback power on punches and latches, and he has superb hand carriage, nuance, and synergetic feel in pass protection. He's better suited in pass-heavy schemes with his skill set, but Mahlman has a sound two-phase profile, and projects as a potential starter.

name: Jack Velling
analysis:
Jack Velling enters his senior year at Michigan State coming off a 36-411-1 receiving line in 2024. At 6'4", 256 pounds, Velling excels as a vertical seam threat and middle-of-the-field target, leveraging his sizable catch radius and toughness working through traffic to consistently find soft spots in zone coverage. While he lacks top-end speed and acceleration, limitations that can leave him stuck in man coverage, Velling’s sure hands, ability to track passes, and knack for uncovering in space make him a reliable, high-IQ weapon.

He profiles as a dependable chain-mover and steady red-zone target with the skill set to carve out an NFL role as a complementary tight end.
